---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { appsAccentColor } from '../../config/colors';
---

<BaseLayout title="GreenScope" description="Software Carbon Intensity observability for the dreamfold.dev platform">
  <div class="max-w-[var(--max-width)] mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
    <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <!-- Header with accent -->
      <header class="mb-8 pb-6 border-b-2" style={`border-color: ${appsAccentColor};`}>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-[var(--color-heading)]">GreenScope</h1>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">Software Carbon Intensity observability for the dreamfold.dev platform</p>
      </header>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none
        prose-headings:text-[var(--color-heading)]
        prose-p:text-[var(--color-text)]
        prose-a:text-[var(--color-accent)]
        prose-strong:text-[var(--color-heading)]
        prose-li:text-[var(--color-text)]
      ">

        <p>
          Every application running on dreamfold.dev consumes energy and generates carbon emissions. GreenScope measures this impact using the Green Software Foundation's Software Carbon Intensity (SCI) specification, turning infrastructure metrics into a single, comparable score: grams of CO2 equivalent per HTTP request.
        </p>

        <p class="text-sm font-medium px-4 py-3 rounded-lg bg-[var(--color-translucent)]">
          Live at <a href="https://sci.dreamfold.dev">sci.dreamfold.dev</a>.
          Implements the <a href="https://sci-guide.greensoftware.foundation/">SCI Specification</a> from the Green Software Foundation.
        </p>

        <h2>The SCI Formula</h2>
        <p>
          SCI = ((E &times; I) + M) / R. Energy consumed (E) multiplied by grid carbon intensity (I), plus embodied hardware emissions (M), divided by a functional unit (R) — in this case, HTTP requests. The result is a normalised carbon cost per unit of useful work.
        </p>

        <h2>Real-Time Grid Carbon</h2>
        <p>
          Carbon intensity varies throughout the day as the UK electricity grid shifts between gas, wind, solar, and nuclear. GreenScope fetches real-time marginal intensity from the National Grid ESO Carbon Intensity API every calculation cycle, so SCI scores reflect the actual carbon cost of electricity at the time of use.
        </p>

        <h2>Per-App Scoring</h2>
        <p>
          Each application on the platform — EVM, EquiCalendar, meWeb — gets its own SCI score. CPU usage is collected per container via Prometheus and cAdvisor, then converted to energy using the host CPU's thermal design power. This means you can compare the carbon efficiency of different apps and track improvements over time.
        </p>

        <h2>Embodied Emissions</h2>
        <p>
          Manufacturing a server has a carbon footprint too. GreenScope allocates a proportional share of the host hardware's total embodied emissions to each app based on how much CPU time it consumes relative to the total available. This follows the SCI spec's time-share and resource-share model.
        </p>

        <h2>Full Transparency</h2>
        <p>
          The SCI specification requires disclosure of methodology, assumptions, and software boundaries. GreenScope's methodology page documents every formula, configured value, data source, and limitation. Nothing is hidden behind a "green" label without explanation.
        </p>

        <h2>Tech Stack</h2>
        <p>
          Python and FastAPI backend with SQLite for historical storage. Prometheus and cAdvisor for container metrics collection. UK Carbon Intensity API for real-time grid data. Chart.js for trend visualisation. Custom Prometheus gauges for SCI metrics, integrated into the shared Grafana dashboards. Fully containerised with Docker.
        </p>

        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
          SCI scores are estimates based on CPU energy modelling. Actual energy consumption may differ — see the methodology page for full details on assumptions and limitations.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
